<subSubSection id="5136012FAF8A8B920EC8852DA3DE2788" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="E06FDFF6A04053BC5E40C3D5AA75D044" pageNumber="248">
Chiapas, soil. This is a handsome black ant displaying often quite brilliant satiny blue metallescence. A greasy specimen from Guatemala in the Wheeler Collection shows none of this blue reflection, and Emery did not mention it in the original description. The habitus is quite different from that of species like 
<taxonomicName id="078B025D906EA6232E45667FD5C19A8F" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138873" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera opaciceps Mayr" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="opaciceps">Ponera opaciceps Mayr</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="2EF73D6F3B59964B9145E5C2DF391458" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:228145" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Manual - Ponera trigona" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="trigona">Ponera trigona Mayr</taxonomicName>
, and it would not be surprising if 
<taxonomicName id="D13F85D494DE5B9EF209A61BD5792FBE" LSID-HNS="urn:lsid:biosci.ohio-state.edu:osuc_concepts:138864" class="Insecta" family="Formicidae" genus="Ponera" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName-HNS="Ponera nitidula Emery" order="Hymenoptera" pageNumber="248" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="nitidula">Ponera nitidula</taxonomicName>
were eventually shown to represent part of a distinct subgenus.
</paragraph>
